uses_data: The collected data in this study consists of a comprehensive human brain proteomic dataset. It includes sample metadata, mass spectrometry raw files, a FASTA database, and TMT protein quantification results. All of these files have been deposited on Synapse and can be accessed through the provided data citations. The dataset serves as a valuable resource for various research endeavors, including protein expression analysis and the identification of novel brain-specific splice variants, coding changes, and single nucleotide variants. Researchers can utilize this dataset to determine the abundance of their protein of interest in the human brain and to search for alternative transcripts and start sites at the protein level.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected using a proteome-wide quantitation approach with two global reference internal standards (GIS). Each protein in the dataset has its own GIS measurement. Outliers were identified as proteins whose GIS measurement was 4 standard deviations away from the mean value in any given subsection. The number of proteins remaining after filtering based on this criterion is shown in Supplementary Table 6. 

To assess quantitative consistency across batches, the distribution of proteins was investigated based on the average of two normalized GIS signal abundances. In the anterior cingulate, the protein distribution was similar across all 5 batches, with more than half of the proteins generating signal abundances greater than 100 (log 10 of 2). However, in the frontal cortex dataset, the protein distribution between batches differed. Protein abundances in batch 1 and batch 4 showed a similar distribution to all batches derived from the cingulate cortex.

The dataset, including sample metadata, mass spectrometry raw files, the FASTA database, and TMT protein quantification results, has been deposited on Synapse and the ProteomeXchange Consortium. The dataset identifier is provided.

In terms of technical validation, the dataset achieved deep coverage of the human brain proteome, with approximately 8,000 protein groups identified in each batch. A total of 127,321 unique peptides were identified, mapping to 11,840 protein groups at a 1% false discovery rate (FDR) on the peptide spectrum match (PSM) level across all samples. This represented 10,230 coding gene products. The overlap of the proteomic data with available brain-specific RNA-seq data was also evaluated, showing the depth of the dataset. RNA transcript abundances were calculated as transcripts per million (TPM) reads, which allows for comparison between samples of different origins and composition.
collection_team_type: Internal team
collection_team_demographic: No, there is no mention of demographic information about the team who collects the data.
collection_sources: The data has been collected from human brain tissue samples, specifically from the frontal cortex and anterior cingulate gyrus brain regions.
collection_infrastructure: The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include TMT labeling, off-line ERLIC fractionation, SPS-MS3 analysis on an Orbitrap Fusion mass spectrometer, RNA-seq for gene detection, peptide reference standards, and the use of programs like WeiGhted Co-expression Network Analysis (WGCNA) for protein co-expression analysis.
annotation_explanation:
The annotation process done over the data involves several use cases. 

Use case 1 focuses on protein expression and provides a reference for protein expression values. It allows investigators to determine if their protein of interest is abundantly expressed in the human brain.

Use case 3 involves protein co-expression network analysis. Programs like WeiGhted Co-expression Network Analysis (WGCNA) are used to analyze protein expression patterns and identify groups of proteins (modules) that correlate to molecular and biological functionalities, cellular localization, and cellular origin. These programs can also correlate protein modules to case traits, such as clinical status and pathological burden, to understand the connection between protein co-expression and clinical diagnosis.

Use case 4 involves the identification and quantification of post-translational modifications (PTMs). The dataset allows for the detection of highly abundant disease-specific PTMs on key substrates in Alzheimer's and Parkinson's Disease. While enrichment strategies would provide a more complete PTM profile, this dataset serves as a starting point to identify the most abundant types of modifications for prioritization in future biological assays.

Overall, the annotation process involves quantifying protein expression, analyzing protein co-expression networks, and identifying post-translational modifications in the dataset.

uses_data: The collected data consists of T1-weighted MRI images of 304 subjects, with a standardized subset of 229 subjects. The full raw dataset is archived with the Archive of Disability Data to Enable Policy research at the Inter-university Consortium for Political and Social Research (ICPSR), while the standardized subset is archived with the 1,000 Functional Connectomes Project International Data Sharing Initiative (FCP-INDI). The dataset includes information on scanner strength, brand, and image resolution. The average lesion volume across all cohorts is 2.128 ± 3.898 × 10^4 mm^3, with a minimum lesion size of 10 mm^3 and a maximum lesion size of 2.838 × 10^5 mm^3. The dataset contains both single and multiple lesions per individual, with slightly more than half of the subjects having only one lesion. Lesions are distributed roughly equally between the left and right hemispheres, with more subcortical lesions than cortical lesions. The dataset is intended for testing and comparing the performance of different lesion segmentation techniques and identifying barriers hindering the performance of automated lesion segmentation algorithms. Researchers can access the data through the ICPSR and FCP-INDI archives, and are encouraged to properly cite the original authors and research labs. Various tools and resources are available for viewing, annotating, segmenting, and quantifying the data. Users are cautioned against overfitting training algorithms to this dataset and future work aims to provide additional test datasets for algorithm testing.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected from research groups in the ENIGMA Stroke Recovery Working Group consortium. A total of 304 MRI images from 11 cohorts worldwide were collected. These images consisted of T1-weighted anatomical MRIs of individuals after stroke. The collection of these images was primarily for research purposes and may not be representative of the overall general stroke population. 

For each MRI image, brain lesions were identified and masks were manually drawn on each individual brain in native space using MRIcron, an open-source tool for brain imaging visualization and defining volumes of interest. At least one lesion mask was identified for each individual MRI, and if additional separate lesions were identified, they were traced as separate masks. 

An expert neuroradiologist reviewed all lesions to provide additional qualitative descriptions of the type of stroke, primary lesion location, vascular territory, and intensity of white matter disease. A separate tracer performed quality control on each lesion mask, which included assessing the accuracy of the lesion segmentations, revising the lesion mask if needed, and categorizing the lesions to generate additional data such as the number of lesions in left and right hemispheres, and in cortical and subcortical regions. 

The dataset is provided in native subject space and is archived with the Archive of Disability Data to Enable Policy research at the Inter-university Consortium for Political and Social Research (ICPSR). A standardized, defaced subset of the dataset is also archived with the 1,000 Functional Connectomes Project International Data Sharing Initiative (FCP-INDI). The ICPSR provides access to the data and technical assistance, while the FCP-INDI hosts many widely available neuroimaging datasets. 

The full dataset archived with ICPSR follows a naming convention and description of the files in ATLAS R1.1. Each subject folder within the dataset contains the original T1-weighted MRI image, as well as three masks for the main lesion: the unsmoothed lesion mask, and two smoothed lesion masks in different formats. If a subject had multiple lesions, there would be additional lesion masks for each lesion. 

In the FCP-INDI archive, the dataset follows the Brain Imaging Data Structure (BIDS) naming convention and the images have been normalized to a standard MNI-152 template, intensity normalized, and defaced. 

The dataset is fully de-identified by removing all HIPAA-protected health information identifiers, and all data were visually inspected before release. Informed consent was obtained from all subjects, and the data sharing agreements were approved by the University of Southern California's technology transfer office. 

Researchers using the dataset should acknowledge the contributions of the original authors and research labs by properly citing the article and the data repository link. The dataset can be accessed through ICPSR and FCP-INDI, and additional tools and resources are available for viewing and analyzing the data. Users are encouraged to be cautious of overfitting training algorithms to this dataset and future work will aim to provide additional test datasets for users to properly test their algorithms on untrained data.
collection_team_type: The data was collected by an internal team.
collection_team_demographic: No, there is no mention of demographic information about the team who collects the data.
collection_sources: The data has been collected from the Archive of Disability Data to Enable Policy research at the Inter-university Consortium for Political and Social Research (ICPSR) and the 1,000 Functional Connectomes Project International Data Sharing Initiative (FCP-INDI).
collection_infrastructure:
The tools and devices used during the collection process include:
- MRI machines to capture T1-weighted MRI images
- Hand-tracing software (MRIcron) to create lesion masks
- Gaussian smoothing kernel for creating smoothed lesion masks
- MRICron software for further editing the masks
- NIfTI format for storing the MRI images
- Brain Imaging Data Structure (BIDS) naming convention for the standardized dataset
- NITRC website for downloading MRIcron software
- BrainBox web application for viewing and annotating neuroimaging data
- SRQL package of scripts for quantification and analysis of lesions
- GitHub page for accessing additional releases of data or software and submitting issues or feedback.
annotation_explanation: The annotation process for the ATLAS dataset involved manually segmenting diverse lesions from T1-weighted MRIs. The lesions were segmented using the NITRC open source software MRIcron. Additionally, a package of scripts called SRQL (Semi-automated Robust Quantification of Lesions) was created to provide further correction for human errors in lesion tracing and to output descriptive statistics on lesions. The dataset includes information on the distribution of lesions, such as single versus multiple lesions per individual, and the location of the lesions (left hemisphere, right hemisphere, subcortical, cortical, etc.). The dataset also includes metadata such as scanner information and image resolution. The annotation process is described in Figure 1 of the document, and an example of lesion segmentation in MRICron is shown in Figure 2.

uses_uses:
The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
1. Assessments into the functioning and impacts of dams.
2. Identifying the catchments supplying water and sediment to dams.
3. Understanding the impacts of climate change, land use change, and land management interventions in the watershed.
4. Validating the number of dams in areas with low-resolution imagery.
5. Comparing the number of dams in different countries with other data sources.
6. Carrying out spatial and hydrological analyses.
7. Including smaller dams that are omitted by other registers.

uses_data: The collected data is a global dataset of more than 38,000 georeferenced dams. The data includes the location of dam walls, which can be useful for machine learning approaches to dam identification from imagery. Additionally, a global vector file of the watershed for each dam is provided. The dataset is available as Esri Shapefiles using the World Geodetic System 1984 (WGS84) datum and geographic coordinate system. The dam IDs in the dataset match the corresponding catchment IDs in the attribute tables. The only attribute data provided are the latitude and longitude of dam locations. The dataset is available on the figshare repository and through the Global Dam Watch data portal hosted by King's College London. The dataset was developed through systematic digitization of satellite imagery globally by a small team. The paper also highlights the approaches used for bias estimation and data validation.
collection_explanation:
The dataset used in this study is called the Global Reservoir and Dam (GOODD) database. The collection process of this dataset involved digitizing global dams using the Google Earth geobrowser. The dams were digitized by scanning through one by one degree tiles on Google Earth using a GeoWiki coded in KML (Keyhole Markup Language) and linked to an online database. This allowed multiple users to add to the database without interfering with each other's efforts and provided a clear indication of which areas were complete and which areas still needed to be scanned.

The majority of the digitizing was carried out between 2007 and 2011, with additional updates in 2016. The 2011 database was updated for each continent using updated national registers for India and the US National Inventory of Dams database. Other sources, such as a spreadsheet of major dams in China developed by International Rivers and web-based sources for individual countries, were also used. A cross-check with the GranD v1.1 database was conducted, and any dams not already included in the GOODD database were added from Google Earth imagery.

To identify likely locations of dams based on their reservoirs, a Google Earth visualization of the Shuttle Radar Topography Mission (SRTM) Water Body Dataset (SWBD) was used as a guide in the digitizing process. Each digitized dam wall location was saved as a precise latitude and longitude and was attributed a unique ID number.

A minimum dam size criteria was established for inclusion in the database. This criteria was based on the resolution of the Google Earth imagery available globally during the time of digitizing. A pilot study with 100 dams from the US National Inventory of Dams database showed that a reservoir length of 500 meters and a dam wall length of 150 meters for small dams could be identified with certainty from this low-resolution imagery.

The dataset is available on the figshare repository and through an unrestricted data repository hosted by King's College London. The data is provided as Esri Shapefiles using the World Geodetic System 1984 (WGS84) datum and geographic coordinate system. The dataset includes point data for dam locations and polygon data for the catchments. Dam IDs match the corresponding catchment IDs in the attribute tables of the datasets. The only attribute data provided are the latitude and longitude of dam locations.

annotation_explanation:
The annotation process for the data involved systematic digitization of satellite imagery globally by a small team. The team identified and marked the coordinates for the location of dam walls. This raw digitized coordinate data can be useful for machine learning approaches to dam identification from imagery. Additionally, a global vector file of the watershed for each dam was created. 

To validate the data, a number of 1-degree tiles were digitized a second time by a different contributor. This was done to account for potential differences between contributors in identifying and including dams in the database. The imagery used in the digitization process was ensured to be the same by looking at the date when the tile was finished and setting the imagery date on Google Earth accordingly. On average, more than 80% of dams were found by both contributors, indicating a high level of agreement in the annotation process.

uses_data_limits: Yes, the context mentions that the monthly-mean character of the macroclimatic data on which these datasets are based must be borne in mind when applying them to ecological problems. This implies that there are limitations to generalizing the data to other ecological problems.
uses_represents_people: No. The data of the dataset represents microclimatic conditions needed to compute heat and water balances of organisms in terrestrial environments.
uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are not humans. The dataset consists of gridded hourly estimates of microclimatic conditions, which are environmental variables related to climate.
uses_data: The collected data consists of gridded hourly estimates of microclimatic conditions such as air temperature, wind speed, relative humidity, solar radiation, sky radiation, and substrate temperatures from the surface to 1 m depth. The dataset covers the entire globe at a high resolution of approximately 15 km. The estimates are based on long-term average macroclimates and are provided for the middle day of each month. Each pixel in the dataset includes six shade levels and three generic substrates (soil, rock, and sand). These data can be used to derive biophysical estimates of the heat, water, and activity budgets of terrestrial organisms. The dataset can be interpolated to obtain estimates at finer resolutions of time (sub-hourly or daily) and heights above the ground between 1 cm and 120 cm if needed. The dataset does not include simulations of snow cover, so adjustments may be necessary for accurate soil temperature estimates in snow-covered areas. The data have been validated against observations of soil temperature and surface minimum temperature at various sites in Australia and the USA, showing good agreement with the observations.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected by using a microclimate model that was tested against Australian 3-hourly observations of soil temperature and surface minimum temperature. The observations were collected by the Bureau of Meteorology at 43 sites across Australia from 2000 to 2009. The model predicted 85% of the variation in the soil temperature observations with an average accuracy of 2-3.3 °C. Historical daily interpolated climatic grids and monthly soil moisture estimates were used as environmental inputs for the validation study. 

To compare the performance of the model using the environmental inputs of the present study, a 3-year simulation was run based on a daily spline of the monthly inputs. The resulting outputs were compared to the observations and predictions reported in a previous study for four climatically distinct sites. The outputs were found to be extremely similar, with more variation predicted and observed with the daily resolution data at shallow depths. 

In addition to the Australian tests, the outputs of the model were compared for 177 sites across the USA. 3-hourly soil temperature estimates from these sites were extracted from the Soil Climate Analysis Network using data from 2011-2013. The same procedure as the Australian tests was followed, and the model predicted 88% of the variation in the soil temperature observations with an accuracy of 3.2-4.5 °C. 

The dataset provides hourly estimates of microclimatic conditions needed to compute heat and water balances of organisms in terrestrial environments at a global scale. It complements existing gridded datasets of macroclimate for correlative species distribution modelling. The dataset can be used to extract data for specific points or selected grids, and interpolation functions can be used to obtain estimates at finer resolutions of time, shade level, and heights above the ground.

annotation_explanation: The annotation process done over the data involves the creation of a gridded dataset of hourly estimates of microclimatic conditions needed to compute heat and water balances of organisms in terrestrial environments at a global scale. This dataset, called 'microclim', complements existing gridded datasets of macroclimate for correlative species distribution modeling. The microclimatic conditions include variables such as air temperature, wind speed, radiation, humidity, and substrate (soil) surface temperature. The dataset provides information on these variables for different months and times of the day, allowing for a detailed understanding of the microclimatic environments experienced by organisms. The annotation process likely involved collecting and analyzing data from various sources, such as weather stations and soil climate analysis networks, and using statistical methods to generate the gridded dataset.

uses_uses:
The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
1. Further materials screening and data mining.
2. Training of machine learning (ML) models.
3. Data analysis and artificial intelligence applications.
uses_ml_approach: No, there is no mention about any test using a machine learning approach.
uses_data_limits: No, there is no mention about non-recommended uses or generalization limits of the data.
uses_represents_people: No. The data of the dataset does not represent people.
uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are not humans. The dataset consists of information about two-dimensional (2D) materials, their structures, properties, and synthesis methods.
uses_data:
The collected data in 2DMatPedia consists of information about two-dimensional (2D) materials. The dataset includes various key variables such as the material's name, data type, and a short description. Each unique 2D material in the dataset is identified by a "material_id", and there is also a "relative_id" that provides a link to the material from which the 2D material is obtained. The dataset indicates whether the 2D material is generated through a "top-down" or "bottom-up" process. The relaxed structure of each material is provided in a dictionary format, which can be easily transferred to different formats using pymatgen. Other information that can be deduced from the structure, such as the chemical formula, number of elements, list of elements, space group, and point group, are also included for easy querying.

The dataset also includes documented electronic, energetic, and magnetic properties of the 2D materials. These properties include the bandgap, whether the gap is direct or indirect, whether the material is a metal, energy per atom, van der Waals energy per atom, exfoliation energy per atom, decomposition energy per atom, and total magnetization. The exfoliation energies and calculated structures have been contributed to the Materials Project.

The dataset can be accessed through the web interface of 2DMatPedia, and a JSON file is available for download. The dataset is also integrated with the Materials Project, allowing users to discover 2DMatPedia's data through the Materials Project's programmatic and web search interfaces. Crystallographic Information Files (CIFs) for the structures contributed by 2DMatPedia and the Materials Project are provided for download.

The collected data has been validated by benchmarking the structures and energies against data in the JARVIS database. The calculated lattice parameters and exfoliation energies of a subset of materials that are present in both 2DMatPedia and JARVIS show good agreement. The decomposition energies of experimentally grown 2D materials have also been analyzed, and the distribution of decomposition energies for materials obtained through top-down and bottom-up approaches is shown. The dataset includes both stable and less stable 2D structures, as less stable structures may still have useful functionalities and can potentially be stabilized by other means.

Overall, the collected data in 2DMatPedia provides comprehensive information about 2D materials, including their structures, properties, and synthesis methods.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected through a combination of top-down and bottom-up approaches. 

In the top-down approach, the researchers screened all possible layered bulk materials from the Materials Project database using a topology-based algorithm. They then theoretically exfoliated these bulk materials into monolayers to generate new 2D materials. 

In the bottom-up approach, the researchers systematically generated new 2D materials by substituting elements in known 2D materials with others from the same group in the periodic table. 

The structural, electronic, and energetic properties of these 2D materials were consistently calculated using a standard workflow designed by the Materials Project. This workflow includes parameters for energy cutoff, k-point mesh, and energy convergence threshold that have been extensively tested by the Materials Project. 

To validate the results, the researchers benchmarked the structures and energies against data in an existing 2D material database called JARVIS. They also analyzed the calculated decomposition energies for 59 experimentally grown 2D materials. 

Overall, the dataset contains more than 6,000 monolayer structures of 2D materials obtained through both top-down and bottom-up approaches. The structural, electronic, and energetic properties of these materials have been calculated using a validated computational methodology. The dataset is publicly available at http://www.2dmatpedia.org/.
collection_team_type: The data was collected by an internal team.
collection_team_demographic: No, there is no mention of demographic information about the team who collects the data.
collection_sources: The data has been collected from the Materials Project, Inorganic Crystal Structure Database (ICSD), Crystallographic Open Database (COD), NIST's Joint Automated Repository for Various Integrated Simulations (JARVIS), and high-throughput density functional calculations.
collection_infrastructure:
The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include:

- Flamyngo: A web interface implemented using Flamyngo was used for the 2DMatPedia database.
- Web Interface: The data records can be accessed through the web interface of 2DMatPedia.
- JSON File: A JSON file containing the data is available for download on the web interface and in a Figshare repository.
- Figshare Repository: The JSON file is also available in a Figshare repository.
- Materials Project: The dataset's landing page on the Materials Project portal is used to compare exfoliation energies from 2DMatPedia to the DFT section of NIST's JARVIS.
- MPContribs Portal: The landing page on the MPContribs Portal provides an overview table that links materials details pages on MP to the corresponding details pages on 2DMatPedia and JARVIS-DFT.
- Crystallographic Information Files (CIFs): CIFs for structures contributed by 2DMatPedia and JARVIS-DFT are provided for download.
- High-throughput Calculations: High-throughput density functional calculations were performed to obtain the structural, electronic, and energetic properties of the 2D materials in the database.
- Top-down Approach: A geometry-based algorithm was used to identify layered structures among the bulk materials in the Materials Project, which were then theoretically exfoliated to 2D monolayers.
- Bottom-up Approach: Elemental substitution was systematically applied to the unary and binary 2D materials obtained from the top-down approach to generate new 2D materials.
annotation_explanation:
The annotation process done over the data in 2DMatPedia involves the following steps:

1. Benchmarking: The structures and energies of the 2D materials in 2DMatPedia are benchmarked against data in the JARVIS database. This ensures that the calculations are accurate and reliable.

2. Validation: The calculated decomposition energies for experimentally grown 2D materials are analyzed. The standard workflow designed by the Materials Project is applied, which includes parameters for energy cutoff, k-point mesh, and energy convergence threshold. This validation process ensures that the calculated properties are consistent with experimental data.

3. Comparison: The calculated lattice parameters and exfoliation energies of a subset of materials that are present in both 2DMatPedia and the JARVIS database are compared. The results show a small difference between the two databases, indicating the reliability of the calculations in 2DMatPedia.

4. Distribution Analysis: The distribution of decomposition energies for 2D materials obtained from both top-down and bottom-up approaches is analyzed. The analysis shows the stability of the materials and their suitability for different applications.

5. Performance Evaluation: The performance of the top-down and bottom-up approaches in predicting structures and energies of 2D materials is evaluated. The results demonstrate the complementary roles of these approaches in discovering new 2D materials.

Overall, the annotation process in 2DMatPedia involves rigorous benchmarking, validation, comparison, and analysis to ensure the accuracy and reliability of the calculated properties of the 2D materials.

uses_uses:
The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
1. Quality control and assurance of in situ data, including examining the distribution of mean lake temperatures, identifying outliers, and detecting technical errors during the assembly of the dataset.
2. Assessment of sampling gap impacts on temperature trends, including estimating the amount of error attributable to differences in sampling interval and constructing a relationship between sampling interval and error in temperature estimates.
3. Validation of satellite data with in situ measurements, including comparing summertime mean values, interannual anomalies, and trends between satellite and in situ data.

uses_data:
The collected data for this dataset consists of information on various lakes, including lake location, surroundings, and the individuals who collected the data. The actual values of the data are stored in a separate table and can be linked to the lake information using a siteID column. The dataset also includes processing log files that explain any extrapolation performed as part of the calculations for mean summer temperatures. The data and metadata are documented in the Ecological Metadata Language (EML) and can be accessed through various sources, including the Long Term Ecological Research Network Information System, the DataONE website, and the R package 'laketemps'.

To ensure the quality of the assembled dataset, several steps were taken. First, the distribution of mean lake temperatures was examined using histograms and maps. Outliers and unusual observations or spatial patterns were identified through these visualizations. The histograms and maps were reviewed by all co-authors to maximize the chances of identifying erroneous values. Additionally, the geomorphometric data in the dataset were independently checked against reputable sources by several individuals. The derived mean summer temperatures and geomorphometric data were also shared with the original data providers, who were asked to validate the values included in the dataset. Inconsistencies in the data were resolved by working directly with the original data providers.

The dataset includes data from various sources, including government agencies, research institutions, and environmental organizations. The data collection efforts span over 25 years and involve numerous field and research scientists. The dataset also includes data from international collaborations, such as the Lake Baikal dataset collected by Irkutsk State University staff and supported by the Russian Ministry of Education and Science, and data from lakes in Austria, Estonia, Switzerland, and other countries.

The dataset is supported by funding and other support from various organizations, including government agencies, research foundations, and international programs. The dataset is accompanied by figures that provide visual representations of the lakes included in the dataset, the temporal data coverage of summer mean water temperatures, the instrumentation used for temperature measurements in specific lakes, the interpolation methods used to calculate daily temperature estimates, and the mean sampling intervals for the in situ sampled lakes.

Overall, the collected data for this dataset have undergone quality control and assurance measures, including visual examination, independent validation, and collaboration with original data providers. The dataset is well-documented and can be accessed through multiple platforms.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected through a multi-step process to ensure quality control and assurance. The assembly of the dataset was done using scripts in the R programming language. After the dataset was assembled, histograms and maps were used to examine the distribution of mean lake temperatures. The histograms helped identify outliers, while the maps provided geographic plots to identify any unusual observations or spatial patterns that could indicate technical errors during the assembly process. All co-authors examined the histograms and maps to maximize the chances of identifying erroneous values.

To ensure the accuracy of the geomorphometric data in the dataset, several individuals independently checked the values against reputable sources. The final step in assuring the quality of the dataset was to share the derived mean summer temperatures and geomorphometric data with the original data providers. An email was sent to each data provider containing the relevant data for their lake(s) along with a request to validate the values included in the dataset. This step allowed for feedback from individuals who are most familiar with the lakes in the dataset. Inconsistencies in the data were resolved by working directly with the original data provider.

Overall, the collection process involved assembling the dataset using scripts, examining the distribution of mean lake temperatures through histograms and maps, independent checks of the geomorphometric data, and validation of the data with the original data providers.

collection_sources:
The data has been collected from the following sources or subjects:

- Lake Baikal data collected by Irkutsk State University staff
- Austrian lakes data from the Austrian Hydrological Survey
- Lake Vättern data provided by Vättern's Water Protection Association
- Dorset Environmental Science Centre lakes sampled under the supervision of Robert Girard, Ron Ingram, Norman Yan, and Andrew Paterson
- New York City drinking water reservoirs data sampled and provided by the New York City Department of Environmental Protection (NYCDEP)
- Lakes Peipsi and Võrtsjärv data provided by the Estonian Meteorological and Hydrological Institute
- Loch Leven data published by Dudley et al. (2013)
- Plusssee data collected by the Max-Planck-Institute for Limnology, Ploen until 2006
- Swiss lakes data provided by the City of Zurich Water Supply (WVZ) and the Amt für Abfall, Wasser, Energie und Luft (AWEL) of the Canton of Zurich
- Lakes Annecy, Bourget, and Geneva data from the Information System of the SOERE OLA, INRA Thonon les Bains, CIPEL, CISALB, SILA
- Lake Constance data provided by the Institut für Seenforschung, Langenargen (Intenationale Gewässerschutzkommission für den Bodensee -IGKB)
- Sudbury area lakes sampled by the Cooperative Freshwater Ecology Unit at Laurentian University, under the supervision of Bill Keller and Norman Yan
collection_infrastructure: The tools and devices used during the collection process include R programming language scripts, histograms, maps, and email communication.
annotation_explanation:
The annotation process for the data involved several steps to ensure quality control and assurance. 

First, the dataset was assembled using scripts in the R programming language. After the assembly was complete, the distribution of mean lake temperatures was examined using histograms and maps. The histograms helped identify outliers, while the maps provided geographic plots to identify unusual observations or spatial patterns that could indicate technical errors during the dataset assembly.

To maximize the chances of identifying erroneous values, the histograms and maps were examined by all co-authors. Additionally, the geomorphometric data in the dataset were independently checked by several individuals against reputable sources to ensure accuracy.

The final step in assuring the quality of the dataset was to share the derived mean summer temperatures and geomorphometric data with the original data providers. Each data provider was sent an email containing the relevant data for their lake(s) and a request to validate the values included in the completed dataset. Inconsistencies in the data were resolved by working directly with the original data provider.

Overall, the annotation process involved examining the distribution of mean lake temperatures, checking the geomorphometric data against reputable sources, and validating the data with the original data providers.

uses_uses:
The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
1) Analyzing patterns among sites considering spatial autocorrelation at the site scale.
2) Calculating species richness or diversity estimates consistently at the block or transect level.
3) Assessing coverage within different ecoregions using the provided information.
4) Considering spatial autocorrelation in analyses due to the highly clumped nature of the data.
5) Taking into account assumptions relating to species detectability.
6) Applying log transformation to abundance data.
7) Using the dataset for relative comparisons of fish density rather than accurate estimates.

uses_data_limits: Yes, the context mentions that the data should not be regarded as providing accurate estimates of fish density within transect blocks. Biases are largely systematic at the species level, and the data can be used for relative comparisons.

uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are reef fish, not humans.
uses_data: The collected data consists of a reef fish dataset from the Reef Life Survey (RLS). The dataset includes information on taxonomic richness and abundance of reef fish in various marine ecoregions. The data is presented in comma-separated format and is available on the RLS website. The dataset is continuously updated and any errors are corrected as identified. A live version of the dataset is recommended for use, but an archival version is also available on figshare. The data fields in the dataset are described in Table 2 of the document. Users are encouraged to report any errors they identify to the corresponding author for correction and improvement of the dataset.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected through a combination of collaborative surveys with scientific colleagues, targeted field campaigns, and ad-hoc local surveys. Field campaigns involved small groups of divers conducting survey dives over a period of four days to two weeks, under the direction and supervision of a scientist or experienced survey diver. At the end of each field campaign, data were collected from participants and manually checked for accuracy. Uncertain or new species records were reduced to the highest taxonomic resolution for which there was confidence. Ad-hoc surveys by trained divers outside of group field campaigns involved species identification assistance and data transfer via email, with data checks made by a scientist before uploading to the database.

Quality control measures were implemented to ensure the accuracy and consistency of the data. Divers were screened before training to select only the most committed and capable individuals with appropriate SCUBA experience. Training courses were provided to divers without prior scientific training, which included instruction in survey methods and species identification. Trainees practiced surveys with an experienced scientist, and their data were carefully compared and approved before being considered of high consistency. A comparison of data collected by divers without scientific training and experienced scientists showed that the variation between the two groups was nonsignificant.

Following each survey, divers transcribed their data from underwater datasheets onto custom data entry forms in Microsoft Excel. Data checks were performed upon upload to the database, including checks for data structure, completeness, and consistency in metadata among divers. Checks were also made to detect species not previously recorded by RLS divers in that particular region. Taxonomic and distributional data were verified before the addition of new species.

The authors of the paper participated in surveys over many ecoregions, collecting a significant portion of the data in the dataset. This provided a substantial element of consistency in diver participation at the global scale.

Overall, the dataset was collected by a combination of experienced scientists and skilled recreational divers, with rigorous quality control measures in place to ensure the accuracy and consistency of the data.
collection_team_type: The data was collected by a combination of experienced scientists and skilled recreational divers.
collection_team_demographic: No, there is no mention of demographic information about the team who collects the data.
collection_speakers_demographics: Yes, the context provides information about the speech situation, such as the genre (scientific research article), the modality (written), and the topics (biology, biodiversity conservation, data collection).
collection_sources: The data has been collected from collaborative surveys with scientific colleagues worldwide, targeted RLS field campaigns, ad-hoc local surveys by trained RLS divers, and surveys conducted by experienced scientists and skilled recreational divers.
collection_infrastructure: The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the data collection process include collaborative surveys, targeted RLS field campaigns, ad-hoc local surveys by trained RLS divers, underwater datasheets, custom data entry forms in Microsoft Excel, and the RLS database. Additionally, species identification assistance and data transfer occurred via email, and data checks were made by a scientist in the office before uploading data to the database.
annotation_explanation:
The annotation process done over the data involves several considerations. First, the data is based on transect blocks, with two adjacent blocks per complete transect. These blocks can be summed to form a standard 500 m2 survey area. However, multiple transects are usually surveyed within each site, and the number of transects differs between sites. Therefore, when analyzing patterns among sites, spatial autocorrelation at the site scale should be considered.

Options for analyzing the data include aggregating data across blocks and transects within each site or adding SiteCode as a nested spatial factor in statistical models and using summed values within each 500 m2 transect. It is important to note that species richness or diversity estimates may be biased by the varying number of transects surveyed at each site if not calculated consistently at the block or transect level.

Another consideration is the spatial bias in the data. The Australian continent is better sampled than other parts of the world, while high-latitude areas are poorly covered, with no survey data from Antarctica. The number of surveys and sites within each ecoregion is listed in Table 1, which provides a guide to coverage within any given ecoregion. Figure 1 and the site map on the RLS website can also be used for a visual overview of site distribution.

Other considerations for the annotation process include spatial autocorrelation, assumptions relating to species detectability, and the distribution of abundance data. Spatial autocorrelation should be considered for many analyses as the data is highly clumped. Detectability of species may vary due to physical appearance, behavior, or abundance, which should be taken into account. Abundance data have a long distribution tail, and factors typically act in a multiplicative rather than additive way, so log transformation of abundance data is appropriate in most cases.

The annotation process described in associated papers used community level metrics calculated per transect or block and averaged across transects within each site. The random forest methods used to model community metrics were found to be robust to spatial autocorrelation.

The data collection system was designed to monitor and acquire data from industry-standard equipment for electricity, water, natural gas, and climate. The dataset consists of meter readings taken every minute, with associated timestamps.
uses_data: The collected data is stored in a database server and can be downloaded from the online code repository GitHub. The dataset, called AMPds2, is publicly available for download from Harvard Dataverse in various formats including CSV, tab-delimited, and RData. The dataset consists of multiple files, each representing a different type of data (Electricity, Water, NaturalGas, and Climate) and a specific meter ID. Each file contains rows representing meter readings taken every minute, with an associated unix timestamp. The readings include measurements and calculations provided by the meter. In the case of pulse metering, the data acquisition unit calculates three measurements (counter, avg_rate, inst_rate) based on received pulses from each meter. The timestamp is based on the number of seconds since 1970-01-01 12:00:00am (UTC), with each reading being one minute apart. The timestamp may have a slight variation of ±10 seconds, which was corrected by a data cleaning script. The dataset also includes information about major appliances and climate data. Additionally, there is a supplementary dataset available for download, called ODD, which contains readings from various sensors in the test house. The dataset was developed by S.M., with contributions from B.E., I.V.B., and F.P.
collection_explanation: The dataset was collected using industry-standard equipment for monitoring and acquisition. The data was stored off-site on a database server hosted at a co-location facility with proper power backup and network connection redundancy. The data collection system was designed with integrity and accuracy in mind. After two years of collection, only a small number of readings were missing, which were algorithmically created during the data cleaning process. The dataset is publicly available for download in various formats, including CSV, tab-delimited, and RData format. The dataset includes files for electricity, water, natural gas, and climate data. Each file contains a single meter reading once every minute, with an associated unix timestamp. The timestamp represents the number of seconds since 1970-01-01 12:00:00am (UTC). The data acquisition units used the Network Time Protocol (NTP) for clock synchronization, but there were some records where the timestamp was off by ±10 seconds, which were corrected during the data cleaning process. The dataset also includes information about major appliances and utility billing statements.

collection_sources: The data has been collected from industry-standard equipment for monitoring and acquisition.
collection_infrastructure:
The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the data collection process include:

- Industry-standard equipment for monitoring and acquisition
- Data acquisition units
- Database server hosted at a co-location facility with power backup and network connection redundancy
- Code repository on GitHub for storing and downloading data
- Network Time Protocol (NTP) for clock synchronization
- DENT meters with a fixed baud rate of 9600 bps for downloading readings
- Environment Canada for climate data files
- Harvard Dataverse for hosting the dataset files
annotation_explanation:
The annotation process for the data involved several steps. S.M. led the development of the dataset and acquired the necessary information. They also performed data analytics, which included organizing, processing, verifying, and collating the data. B.E. provided algorithmic annotations specifically for the water data and wrote the corresponding section of the manuscript. I.V.B. and F.P. provided mentoring and edited and revised the manuscript.

In terms of code availability, the code used to store the collected data to the database server can be downloaded from the online code repository GitHub. The scripts used to convert the database tables to the final dataset files can also be downloaded from the same online code repository.

The AMPds2 dataset, which includes electricity, water, natural gas, and climate data, is publicly available for download from Harvard Dataverse. The dataset is provided in various formats, such as CSV, tab-delimited, and RData. Each file in the dataset represents a single meter reading taken every minute, with an associated unix timestamp. The dataset files contain measurements and calculations provided by the meters, and specific information on each measurement is provided in Table 4.

For pulse metering, the data acquisition unit calculated three measurements (counter, avg_rate, inst_rate) based on the received pulses from each meter. The timestamp in the dataset represents the number of seconds since 1970-01-01 12:00:00am (UTC), with each reading being one minute apart. The timestamp was occasionally off by ±10 seconds, but a data cleaning script corrected these variations to have zero-seconds.

The dataset also includes utility billing data for electricity and natural gas, which corresponds to utility billing statements found in Electricity_Statements.csv and NaturalGas_Statements.csv, respectively. However, there are no billing statements available for the water data.

The utility billing data was created from the values on redacted utility billing statements. 50% of the billing data was downloaded from the utility's website, while the remaining data was manually entered. All billing data was verified for accuracy from each billing statement, and data entered by hand was rechecked for accuracy.

uses_data:
The collected data for this study includes participants' responses to a questionnaire on basic demographic information, musical preference, proficiency, education, and familiarity with the "Forrest Gump" movie. These responses are stored in a comma-separated value (CSV) file, with each participant's data on one line and questionnaire items as columns. The file also contains participants' responses to the audio quality rating after each movie segment presentation.

In addition to the questionnaire data, fMRI data is also available. The fMRI data is stored in four different flavors, with each movie segment having its own individual 4D image. The raw BOLD data is stored in the file "bold.nii.gz", but it suffers from severe geometric distortions. To address this, distortion-corrected BOLD data is provided in the file "bold_dico.nii.gz". Two additional flavors of the distortion-corrected data are also available, with one aligned using an affine transformation only ("bold_dico_dico7Tad2grpbold7Tad.nii.gz") and the other aligned using non-linear warping ("bold_dico_dico7Tad2grpbold7Tad_nl.nii.gz"). The details of the alignment procedure can be found in the "Technical Validation" section of the paper.

The dataset has been validated for negative effects of the de-identification procedure on subsequent analysis steps. Any known anomalies and their impact on the dataset are detailed in Table 3 of the paper.

The dataset is publicly available and can be used for benchmarking and comparing algorithms for functional parcellation, physiological noise reduction, and tissue segmentation. The authors encourage independent researchers to extend the scope of the dataset by adding data from participants with different cultural backgrounds, spoken languages, or audio-visual stimuli. The authors also plan to add additional modalities to the dataset in the future.

The data files are organized according to the standards implemented by the openfmri.org project. They are shared in documented standard formats, such as NIfTI or plain text files, to enable further processing in any analysis environment without dependencies on proprietary tools. Conversion from the original raw data formats is implemented in publicly accessible scripts, and the type and version of employed file format conversion tools are documented. The results presented in the paper were produced using open-source software on a computational cluster running the (Neuro)Debian operating system. The computational environment and analysis scripts are freely available, providing transparency regarding all aspects of the analyses.

Additional material, including information on data access options, publications that use the dataset, source code for data conversion and processing steps, is available on the study's website. The data is made available under the terms of the Public Domain Dedication and License (PDDL), allowing anyone to download and use the dataset for any purpose. The source code is released under the terms of the MIT license. The authors hope that users of the data will acknowledge the original authors by citing the publication and follow good scientific practice.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected through a combination of fMRI data recording and participant responses to a questionnaire. The fMRI data was collected during a two-hour presentation of the movie "Forrest Gump" using a high field strength of 7 Tesla and a high spatial resolution of 2.75 mm3. The fMRI data is available in four different flavors, each stored in an individual 4D image for each movie segment separately. The raw BOLD data is stored in bold.nii.gz, but it suffers from severe geometric distortions. Therefore, distortion-corrected BOLD data is also provided in bold_dico.nii.gz. Two additional flavors of the distortion-corrected data are available, one aligned by applying an affine transformation only (bold_dico_dico7Tad2grpbold7Tad.nii.gz) and the other aligned by non-linear warping (bold_dico_dico7Tad2grpbold7Tad_nl.nii.gz).

The participants' responses to the questionnaire on basic demographic information, musical preference, proficiency, education, and familiarity with the "Forrest Gump" movie are available in a comma-separated value (CSV) file called Location demographics.csv. The data in this file are structured as one line per participant with questionnaire items as columns. The same file also contains the participants' responses to the audio quality rating after each movie segment presentation.

In addition to the fMRI data and questionnaire responses, auxiliary data has been acquired to associate findings from functional data analyses with structural aspects of the brain. This includes high-resolution structural scans (T1-and T2-weighted), localizers for blood vessels, and diffusion tensor imaging data.

The dataset is organized according to the standards implemented by the openfmri.org project and is shared in documented standard formats, such as NIfTI or plain text files, to enable further processing in arbitrary analysis environments with no imposed dependencies on proprietary tools. The conversion from the original raw data formats is implemented in publicly accessible scripts, and the type and version of employed file format conversion tools are documented. All results presented in the paper were produced by open-source software on a computational cluster running the (Neuro)Debian operating system.

To validate the dataset, all image analyses presented in the paper were performed on the released data to test for negative effects of the de-identification procedure on subsequent analysis steps. Any known anomalies and their impact on the dataset are detailed in Table 3 of the paper.

The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include:

- Openfmri.org project standards for organizing data files
- Standard formats such as NIfTI or plain text files for data sharing
- Publicly accessible scripts for converting raw data formats
- (Neuro)Debian operating system running on a computational cluster
- Open-source software for analysis
- Python programming language for data access module
- Publicly available source code for data conversion and processing steps
- Computational environment available for anyone to use
- Public Domain Dedication and License for data sharing
- MIT license for source code release
- High field strength of 7 Tesla for fMRI data recording
- High spatial resolution of 2.75 mm3 for fMRI data
- Auxiliary data acquisition including high-resolution structural scans, localizers for blood vessels, and diffusion tensor imaging data.
annotation_explanation:
The annotation process for the movie scene data involved the following steps:

1. Location stimulus/task001/annotations/scenes.csv: This file contains annotations for the movie scenes, indicating the location of each scene in the movie.

2. Location demographics.csv: This file contains participants' responses to a questionnaire on basic demographic information, musical preference, proficiency, education, and familiarity with the "Forrest Gump" movie. The data is structured as one line per participant with questionnaire items as columns.

3. German_audio_description.csv: This file provides a transcript of the German audio description for the movie. It includes the timing of the description segments and any special comments or hints related to the description's interference with other dialog or its location in the movie soundtrack.

These annotations were performed on the released data to test for any negative effects of the de-identification procedure on subsequent analysis steps. Any technical problems or anomalies encountered during data acquisition are detailed in Table 3.

uses_uses:
The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
1. To explore semi-supervised and unsupervised methods in the medical and technical communities.
2. To analyze, classify, segment, and retrieve images and videos with specific findings or properties in the field of computer science.
3. To use the labeled data for teaching and training in medical education.
4. To simulate live endoscopies and enable developers to do image classification.
5. To use the dataset for standard machine learning tasks such as classification.
6. To perform experiments and compare results with state-of-the-art methods in GI tract image classification.
7. To investigate and develop new and improved methods for the medical domain using the large number of images available in the dataset.
uses_ml_approach: Yes, the dataset has been tested using different machine learning approaches, including Pre-Trained DenseNet-161, Averaged ResNet-152 + DenseNet-161, Pre-Trained ResNet-50, and ResNet-152 + DenseNet-161 + MLP. These experiments were conducted to provide baseline results for future research comparisons.
uses_data_limits: No, there is no mention about non-recommended uses or generalization limits of the data.
uses_represents_people: No. The data of the dataset does not represent people. It represents images and videos of GI findings in the GI tract.
uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are not humans. The dataset consists of images and videos from various GI examinations, not individuals.
uses_data:
The collected data consists of 110,079 images and 374 videos from various GI examinations, resulting in a total of 1 million images and frames. The dataset is intended for use in detecting, classifying, and segmenting normal and abnormal findings in the GI tract. It is the largest and most diverse dataset of its kind, and it is made available to the research community for further investigation and development of new methods in the medical domain.

The dataset includes both labeled and unlabeled data. The labeled data has been used for research on classification and segmentation of GI findings using computer vision and machine learning approaches. It can also be used for teaching and training in medical education. The ground truths for the labeled data were provided by expert gastroenterologists, making it a valuable learning set for future clinicians.

The unlabeled data is well suited for semi-supervised and unsupervised methods. Recent work in the ML community has shown that algorithms can learn from sparsely labeled and unlabeled data, leading to remarkable improvements in tackling the challenge of lack of data. Semi-supervised learning techniques, such as self-learning and neural graph learning, make use of unlabeled data in addition to a small number of labeled data to extract additional information.

The dataset also includes scripts and text files to help researchers quickly get started using the dataset for standard ML tasks such as classification. Three official splits of the dataset are provided for cross-validation experiments, and the scripts used to generate plots, split data, and generate annotation files are included for reproducibility and transparency.

Overall, the dataset aims to provide a valuable resource for researchers in the field of GI image and video analysis. It not only increases the amount of labeled medical data for supervised learning but also provides a large amount of unlabeled data for semi-supervised and unsupervised methods. The dataset can be used for various tasks such as analysis, classification, segmentation, and retrieval of images and videos with specific findings or properties. It is also open to future contributions, including the publication and sharing of new data.
collection_explanation: The dataset was collected using standard endoscopy equipment from Olympus and Pentax at the Department of Gastroenterology, Baerum Hospital, Vestre Viken Hospital Trust, Norway. The data collection process involved annotating parts of the collected data with class labels and segmentation masks. The annotations were done by experienced gastroenterologists from Baerum hospital, the Cancer Registry of Norway, Karolinska University Hospital in Sweden, and other experienced individuals in the medical field such as junior doctors or Ph.D. students. To address observer variation and potential bias, some findings that are prone to bias were combined into one class. The dataset consists of both labeled and unlabeled images, with a total of 10,662 labeled images and 99,417 unlabeled images from the GI tract. Additionally, segmentation masks and bounding boxes were created for 1,000 images from the polyp class using the Labelbox platform. The annotation process involved pre-segmenting the images by a junior doctor and a Ph.D. student, followed by verification and correction by a gastroenterologist. The dataset was approved by the Norwegian Privacy Data Protection Authority and exempted from patient consent due to full anonymity of the data. The dataset is publicly shareable based on Norwegian and General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) laws. No pre-processing or augmentation was applied to the data.
collection_team_type: The data was collected by an internal team.
collection_team_demographic: No, there is no mention of demographic information about the team who collects the data.
collection_sources:
The data has been collected from the following sources or subjects:

- Labeled images of GI findings
- Segmented images of polyp class
- Unlabeled images
- Extracted global features and unsupervised clustering assignments
- Expert gastroenterologists providing ground truths
- Videos of live endoscopies
- Scripts and text files for ML tasks and classification
- Official splits of the dataset for cross-validation experiments
- Files used to create preliminary experiments
collection_infrastructure:
The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include:

1. Image classification methods: State-of-the-art methods for GI tract image classification were used to evaluate the labeled part of the HyperKvasir dataset. These methods were previously proven to achieve good results in GI tract image classification.

2. Segmentation tools: Segmented images were provided in the dataset, including the original image, a segmentation mask, and a bounding box for 1,000 images from the polyp class. The segmentation mask represents the polyp tissue as foreground pixels, while the background is represented as black pixels. The bounding box defines the outermost pixels of the polyp.

3. JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) file: The bounding boxes for the segmented images are stored in a JSON file.

4. Image and mask folders: The segmented images and their corresponding masks are stored in separate folders, each containing 1,000 JPEG-compressed images.

5. Unlabeled images: The dataset also includes 99,417 unlabeled images, which can be found in the "unlabeled" folder within the image folder.

6. Attribute-Relation File Format (ARFF) files: In addition to the unlabeled image files, the dataset provides extracted global features and possible unsupervised clustering assignments in ARFF files. These files can be processed using machine learning libraries like WEKA or converted into Comma-Separated Values (CSV) files.

7. HyperKvasir Github repository: The dataset includes a series of scripts and text files available in the HyperKvasir Github repository. These files aim to help researchers quickly get started using the dataset for standard machine learning tasks such as classification.

8. Videos: The dataset also includes videos that can be used to simulate live endoscopies, enabling developers to perform image classification as if the video was captured directly from the endoscopes.

9. GitHub repository for the dataset: The GitHub repository for the dataset provides scripts for generating plots, splitting data into different folds, and generating annotation files for reproducibility and transparency.

Overall, the collection process involved the use of image classification methods, segmentation tools, JSON files, folders for segmented and unlabeled images, ARFF files, a GitHub repository, and videos.
annotation_explanation: The annotation process done over the data involved creating class labels for the dataset. The researchers performed experiments using different methods to classify the images in the dataset. The purpose of these experiments was to provide baseline metrics and insight into the dataset's statistical qualities. The researchers also encouraged other researchers to investigate and develop new methods for the medical domain using the dataset. They also mentioned the possibility of creating a larger labeled dataset or performing failure analysis to improve the accuracy of the models. The class labels created during the experiments are available in the GitHub repository.
